3. Prediction and Cross-Validation

Choose one model, fit it on the entire dataset and compare its performance with the results of cross-validation.

a. Train the model

Fit the model on the entire dataset and report a measure of performance (AUC for classification, RMSE for linear regression).

Options for fitting the models:

## Use the entire dataset to fit one of these models
# Linear Regression: lm(outcome ~ predictor1 + predictor2, data = fulldata)
# Logistic Regression: lm(outcome ~ predictor1 + predictor2, data = fulldata, family = "binomial")
# k-nearest-neighbor: knn3(outcome ~ predictor1 + predictor2, data = fulldata, k = 5)
# Decision tree: rpart(outcome ~ predictor1 + predictor2, data = fulldata, method = "class")

airplane_type_tree <- rpart(`Type of Travel` ~ `Online boarding` + Age + `Flight Distance`,
                      data = airplane_type,
                      method = "class")

rpart.plot(airplane_type_tree)

Options for finding AUC is building a ROC curve:

b. Perform cross-validation

How would the model perform on new data? Split your data into train/test sets then use a for-loop (like we did in Worksheet 17). Or you can use the function train() and specify to calculate the AUC:

# Choose number of folds: 
k = 10 

# Randomly order rows in the dataset: 
data <- airplane_type[sample(nrow(airplane_type)), ] 

# Create k folds: 
folds <- cut(seq(1:nrow(data)), breaks = k, labels = FALSE)

# Initialize a vector to keep track of the performance: 
perf_k <- NULL

# Use a for loop to get performance for each test set: 
for(i in 1:k){
  # Create train and test sets
    train_not_i <- data[folds != i, ]
    test_i <- data[folds == i, ]
  
  # Train model on train set (all but fold i)
    model_i<- rpart(`Type of Travel` ~ `Online boarding` + Age + `Flight Distance`,
                      data = train_not_i,
                      method = "class")
    
  # Test model on test set (fold i)
    predict_i <- test_i %>%
      mutate(predictions = predict(model_i, test_i)[,2])
  # Consider the ROC curve for the test dataset
    ROC <- ggplot(predict_i) + geom_roc(aes(d = `Type of Travel`, m = predictions))

  # Get performance for fold i (AUC)
    perf_k[i] <- calc_auc(ROC)$AUC}

# Average performance: 
mean(perf_k)
## [1] 0.7081383
